ered a glimpse into the multifaceted world of Hindu worship, life-cycle rites, festivals, performances, gurus, and castes. The book’s final sections deal with the Hinduism that is emerging in diasporic North America and with issues of identity that face Hindus in India and around the world: militancy versus tolerance and the struggle between owning one’s own religion and sharing it with others. Contributors: Andrew Abbott, Michael Burawoy, Patricia Hill Collins, Barbara Ehrenreich, Evelyn Nakano Glenn, Sharon Hays, Douglas Massey, Joya Misra, Orlando Patterson, Frances Fox Piven, Lynn Smith-Lovin, Judith Stacey, Arthur Stinchcombe, Alain Touraine, Immanuel Wallerstein, William Julius Wilson, Robert Zussman  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHinduismxCustoms and practices. 0aHinduismxSocial aspects. 0aReligious lifexHinduism. 7aRELIGION / Hinduism / General.2bisacsh  aasia scholars.  abangalore.  acaste system.  acomparative religion.  adiasporic communities.  adiversity.  aessay collection.  aglobal religions.  aglobalism.  agurus.  ahindu festivals.  ahindu worship.  ahinduism.  ahindus.  aindia.  aindian history.  aindian society.  alife cycles.  alocal traditions.  anonfiction essays.  areligion and culture.  areligious historians.  areligious history.  areligious rites.  areligious scholars.  areligious studies.  areligious traditions.  atheology.1 aAcharya, Kala, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAntarjanam, Lalitambika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBahadur, Om Lata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBharati, Agehananda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCase, Margaret H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/